{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17529394","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17529394"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:55:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:55:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14386"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584057","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584057"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:37:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:37:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14386"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14386","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14386"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.05,0.65,0.05,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7081"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86186"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7081"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14386"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70455"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"107"},{"type":"tags","id":"1336"},{"type":"tags","id":"4279"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16893"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29561"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44418"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86186","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/86186"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-day history of right forearm pain and redness following a dog bite. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She does not smoke cigarettes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 65/min, blood pressure 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 100% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There is a 2 cm area of erythema and swelling over her right forearm with a visible dog bite wound at the centre. There is no oedema of the right forearm or necrotic area. Her tetanus vaccination is up to date.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate antibiotic choice?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral metronidazole","Oral clindamycin","Oral amoxicillin-clavulanic acid","Oral ciprofloxacin","Oral flucloxacillin"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with cellulitis secondary to a dog bite. \u003Cstrong\u003EOral amoxicillin-clavulanic acid\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate antibiotic choice for this presentation. Dog bites can introduce a variety of bacteria into the wound, including \u003Cem\u003EPasteurella\u003C/em\u003E species, \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus\u003C/em\u003E, \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus\u003C/em\u003E, and anaerobes. Amoxicillin-clavulanic acid provides broad-spectrum coverage against both aerobic and anaerobic bacteria commonly found in animal bites, making it the first-line treatment for these infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral metronidazole\u003C/strong\u003E is effective against anaerobic bacteria but lacks coverage for the aerobic organisms commonly found in dog bite wounds. It would be insufficient as monotherapy for this infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral clindamycin\u003C/strong\u003E has good coverage against gram-positive organisms and anaerobes but may not adequately cover \u003Cem\u003EPasteurella\u003C/em\u003E species, which are commonly found in dog bites. It is sometimes used as an alternative in patients with penicillin allergy, but it is not the first-line choice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral ciprofloxacin\u003C/strong\u003E has good gram-negative coverage but is less effective against gram-positive organisms and anaerobes. It is not typically recommended as first-line therapy for dog bites.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral flucloxacillin\u003C/strong\u003E is effective against \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E but does not provide adequate coverage for the other organisms commonly found in dog bite wounds, particularly \u003Cem\u003EPasteurella\u003C/em\u003E species and anaerobes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to antibiotic therapy, management of dog bites should include thorough wound cleaning and debridement if necessary. As Australia is rabies-free, rabies prophylaxis is not required. The patient\u0027s tetanus status should be assessed and updated if necessary, although in this case, it is noted to be up to date.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Amoxicillin-clavulanic acid is the first-line antibiotic for dog bite infections due to its broad spectrum coverage of both aerobic and anaerobic bacteria.","Dog bites can introduce a variety of bacteria into the wound, including Pasteurella, Streptococcus, Staphylococcus, and anaerobes.","Prompt antibiotic treatment is crucial in preventing complications from animal bites, such as cellulitis and deeper tissue infections."],"references":["eTG. Bite wound infections, including clenched-fist injury infections. May 2022. https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/viewTopic?etgAccess=true\u0026guidelinePage=Antibiotic\u0026topicfile=bite-clenched-fist-wound-infections\u0026guidelinename=Antibiotic\u0026sectionId=toc_d1e374#toc_d1e374","Abrahamian FM, Goldstein EJ. Microbiology of animal bite wound infections. Clin Microbiol Rev. 2011 Apr;24(2):231-46. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3122494/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70455"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14386"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70455","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/70455"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-19T19:03:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-19T19:05:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7081"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86186"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"20","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/20"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4c","name":"Plastic Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"creat